2163
2164// This section contains an implementation of struct layout that is, up to the
2165// included tests, compatible with cl.exe (2013). The layout produced is
2166// significantly different than those produced by the Itanium ABI. Here we note
2167// the most important differences.
2168//
2169// * The alignment of bitfields in unions is ignored when computing the
2170// alignment of the union.
2171// * The existence of zero-width bitfield that occurs after anything other than
2172// a non-zero length bitfield is ignored.
2173// * There is no explicit primary base for the purposes of layout. All bases
2174// with vfptrs are laid out first, followed by all bases without vfptrs.
2175// * The Itanium equivalent vtable pointers are split into a vfptr (virtual
2176// function pointer) and a vbptr (virtual base pointer). They can each be
2177// shared with a, non-virtual bases. These bases need not be the same. vfptrs
2178// always occur at offset 0. vbptrs can occur at an arbitrary offset and are
2179// placed after the lexicographically last non-virtual base. This placement
2180// is always before fields but can be in the middle of the non-virtual bases
2181// due to the two-pass layout scheme for non-virtual-bases.
2182// * Virtual bases sometimes require a 'vtordisp' field that is laid out before
2183// the virtual base and is used in conjunction with virtual overrides during
2184// construction and destruction. This is always a 4 byte value and is used as
2185// an alternative to constructor vtables.
2186// * vtordisps are allocated in a block of memory with size and alignment equal
2187// to the alignment of the completed structure (before applying __declspec(
2188// align())). The vtordisp always occur at the end of the allocation block,
2189// immediately prior to the virtual base.
2190// * vfptrs are injected after all bases and fields have been laid out. In
2191// order to guarantee proper alignment of all fields, the vfptr injection
2192// pushes all bases and fields back by the alignment imposed by those bases
2193// and fields. This can potentially add a significant amount of padding.
2194// vfptrs are always injected at offset 0.
2195// * vbptrs are injected after all bases and fields have been laid out. In
2196// order to guarantee proper alignment of all fields, the vfptr injection
2197// pushes all bases and fields back by the alignment imposed by those bases
2198// and fields. This can potentially add a significant amount of padding.
2199// vbptrs are injected immediately after the last non-virtual base as
2200// lexicographically ordered in the code. If this site isn't pointer aligned
2201// the vbptr is placed at the next properly aligned location. Enough padding
2202// is added to guarantee a fit.
2203// * The last zero sized non-virtual base can be placed at the end of the
2204// struct (potentially aliasing another object), or may alias with the first
2205// field, even if they are of the same type.
2206// * The last zero size virtual base may be placed at the end of the struct
2207// potentially aliasing another object.
2208// * The ABI attempts to avoid aliasing of zero sized bases by adding padding
2209// between bases or vbases with specific properties. The criteria for
2210// additional padding between two bases is that the first base is zero sized
2211// or ends with a zero sized subobject and the second base is zero sized or
2212// trails with a zero sized base or field (sharing of vfptrs can reorder the
2213// layout of the so the leading base is not always the first one declared).
2214// This rule does take into account fields that are not records, so padding
2215// will occur even if the last field is, e.g. an int. The padding added for
2216// bases is 1 byte. The padding added between vbases depends on the alignment
2217// of the object but is at least 4 bytes (in both 32 and 64 bit modes).
2218// * There is no concept of non-virtual alignment, non-virtual alignment and
2219// alignment are always identical.
2220// * There is a distinction between alignment and required alignment.
2221// __declspec(align) changes the required alignment of a struct. This
2222// alignment is _always_ obeyed, even in the presence of #pragma pack. A
2223// record inherits required alignment from all of its fields and bases.
2224// * __declspec(align) on bitfields has the effect of changing the bitfield's
2225// alignment instead of its required alignment. This is the only known way
2226// to make the alignment of a struct bigger than 8. Interestingly enough
2227// this alignment is also immune to the effects of #pragma pack and can be
2228// used to create structures with large alignment under #pragma pack.
2229// However, because it does not impact required alignment, such a structure,
2230// when used as a field or base, will not be aligned if #pragma pack is
2231// still active at the time of use.
2232//
2233// Known incompatibilities:
2234// * all: #pragma pack between fields in a record
2235// * 2010 and back: If the last field in a record is a bitfield, every object
2236// laid out after the record will have extra padding inserted before it. The
2237// extra padding will have size equal to the size of the storage class of the
2238// bitfield. 0 sized bitfields don't exhibit this behavior and the extra
2239// padding can be avoided by adding a 0 sized bitfield after the non-zero-
2240// sized bitfield.
2241// * 2012 and back: In 64-bit mode, if the alignment of a record is 16 or
2242// greater due to __declspec(align()) then a second layout phase occurs after
2243// The locations of the vf and vb pointers are known. This layout phase
2244// suffers from the "last field is a bitfield" bug in 2010 and results in
2245// _every_ field getting padding put in front of it, potentially including the
2246// vfptr, leaving the vfprt at a non-zero location which results in a fault if
2247// anything tries to read the vftbl. The second layout phase also treats
2248// bitfields as separate entities and gives them each storage rather than
2249// packing them. Additionally, because this phase appears to perform a
2250// (an unstable) sort on the members before laying them out and because merged
2251// bitfields have the same address, the bitfields end up in whatever order
2252// the sort left them in, a behavior we could never hope to replicate.
2253
2254namespace {

2373MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::ElementInfo
2374MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::getAdjustedElementInfo(
2375 const ASTRecordLayout &Layout) {
2376 ElementInfo Info;
2377 Info.Alignment = Layout.getAlignment();
2378 // Respect pragma pack.
2379 if (!MaxFieldAlignment.isZero())
2380 Info.Alignment = std::min(Info.Alignment, MaxFieldAlignment);
2381 // Track zero-sized subobjects here where it's already available.
2382 EndsWithZeroSizedObject = Layout.endsWithZeroSizedObject();
2383 // Respect required alignment, this is necessary because we may have adjusted
2384 // the alignment in the case of pragam pack. Note that the required alignment
2385 // doesn't actually apply to the struct alignment at this point.
2386 Alignment = std::max(Alignment, Info.Alignment);
2387 RequiredAlignment = std::max(RequiredAlignment, Layout.getRequiredAlignment());
2388 Info.Alignment = std::max(Info.Alignment, Layout.getRequiredAlignment());
2389 Info.Size = Layout.getNonVirtualSize();
2390 return Info;
2391}
2392
2393MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::ElementInfo
2394MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::getAdjustedElementInfo(
2395 const FieldDecl *FD) {
2396 // Get the alignment of the field type's natural alignment, ignore any
2397 // alignment attributes.
2398 ElementInfo Info;
2399 std::tie(Info.Size, Info.Alignment) =
2400 Context.getTypeInfoInChars(FD->getType()->getUnqualifiedDesugaredType());
2401 // Respect align attributes on the field.
2402 CharUnits FieldRequiredAlignment =
2403 Context.toCharUnitsFromBits(FD->getMaxAlignment());
2404 // Respect align attributes on the type.
2405 if (Context.isAlignmentRequired(FD->getType()))
2406 FieldRequiredAlignment = std::max(
2407 Context.getTypeAlignInChars(FD->getType()), FieldRequiredAlignment);
2408 // Respect attributes applied to subobjects of the field.
2409 if (FD->isBitField())
2410 // For some reason __declspec align impacts alignment rather than required
2411 // alignment when it is applied to bitfields.
2412 Info.Alignment = std::max(Info.Alignment, FieldRequiredAlignment);
2413 else {
2414 if (auto RT =
2415 FD->getType()->getBaseElementTypeUnsafe()->getAs<RecordType>()) {
2416 auto const &Layout = Context.getASTRecordLayout(RT->getDecl());
2417 EndsWithZeroSizedObject = Layout.endsWithZeroSizedObject();
2418 FieldRequiredAlignment = std::max(FieldRequiredAlignment,
2419 Layout.getRequiredAlignment());
2420 }
2421 // Capture required alignment as a side-effect.
2422 RequiredAlignment = std::max(RequiredAlignment, FieldRequiredAlignment);
2423 }
2424 // Respect pragma pack, attribute pack and declspec align
2425 if (!MaxFieldAlignment.isZero())
2426 Info.Alignment = std::min(Info.Alignment, MaxFieldAlignment);
2427 if (FD->hasAttr<PackedAttr>())
2428 Info.Alignment = CharUnits::One();
2429 Info.Alignment = std::max(Info.Alignment, FieldRequiredAlignment);
2430 return Info;
2431}

2433void MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::layout(const RecordDecl *RD) {
2434 // For C record layout, zero-sized records always have size 4.
2435 MinEmptyStructSize = CharUnits::fromQuantity(4);
2436 initializeLayout(RD);
2437 layoutFields(RD);
2438 DataSize = Size = Size.alignTo(Alignment);
2439 RequiredAlignment = std::max(
2440 RequiredAlignment, Context.toCharUnitsFromBits(RD->getMaxAlignment()));
2441 finalizeLayout(RD);
2442}
2443
2444void MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::cxxLayout(const CXXRecordDecl *RD) {
2445 // The C++ standard says that empty structs have size 1.
2446 MinEmptyStructSize = CharUnits::One();
2447 initializeLayout(RD);
2448 initializeCXXLayout(RD);
2449 layoutNonVirtualBases(RD);
2450 layoutFields(RD);
2451 injectVBPtr(RD);
2452 injectVFPtr(RD);
2453 if (HasOwnVFPtr || (HasVBPtr && !SharedVBPtrBase))
2454 Alignment = std::max(Alignment, PointerInfo.Alignment);
2455 auto RoundingAlignment = Alignment;
2456 if (!MaxFieldAlignment.isZero())
2457 RoundingAlignment = std::min(RoundingAlignment, MaxFieldAlignment);
2458 if (!UseExternalLayout)
2459 Size = Size.alignTo(RoundingAlignment);
2460 NonVirtualSize = Size;
2461 RequiredAlignment = std::max(
2462 RequiredAlignment, Context.toCharUnitsFromBits(RD->getMaxAlignment()));
2463 layoutVirtualBases(RD);
2464 finalizeLayout(RD);
2465}
2466
2467void MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::initializeLayout(const RecordDecl *RD) {
2468 IsUnion = RD->isUnion();
2469 Size = CharUnits::Zero();
2470 Alignment = CharUnits::One();
2471 // In 64-bit mode we always perform an alignment step after laying out vbases.
2472 // In 32-bit mode we do not. The check to see if we need to perform alignment
2473 // checks the RequiredAlignment field and performs alignment if it isn't 0.
2474 RequiredAlignment = Context.getTargetInfo().getTriple().isArch64Bit()
2475 ? CharUnits::One()
2476 : CharUnits::Zero();
2477 // Compute the maximum field alignment.
2478 MaxFieldAlignment = CharUnits::Zero();
2479 // Honor the default struct packing maximum alignment flag.
2480 if (unsigned DefaultMaxFieldAlignment = Context.getLangOpts().PackStruct)
2481 MaxFieldAlignment = CharUnits::fromQuantity(DefaultMaxFieldAlignment);
2482 // Honor the packing attribute. The MS-ABI ignores pragma pack if its larger
2483 // than the pointer size.
2484 if (const MaxFieldAlignmentAttr *MFAA = RD->getAttr<MaxFieldAlignmentAttr>()){
2485 unsigned PackedAlignment = MFAA->getAlignment();
2486 if (PackedAlignment <= Context.getTargetInfo().getPointerWidth(0))
2487 MaxFieldAlignment = Context.toCharUnitsFromBits(PackedAlignment);
2488 }
2489 // Packed attribute forces max field alignment to be 1.
2490 if (RD->hasAttr<PackedAttr>())
2491 MaxFieldAlignment = CharUnits::One();
2492
2493 // Try to respect the external layout if present.
2494 UseExternalLayout = false;
2495 if (ExternalASTSource *Source = Context.getExternalSource())
2496 UseExternalLayout = Source->layoutRecordType(
2497 RD, External.Size, External.Align, External.FieldOffsets,
2498 External.BaseOffsets, External.VirtualBaseOffsets);
2499}

2501void
2502MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::initializeCXXLayout(const CXXRecordDecl *RD) {
2503 EndsWithZeroSizedObject = false;
2504 LeadsWithZeroSizedBase = false;
2505 HasOwnVFPtr = false;
2506 HasVBPtr = false;
2507 PrimaryBase = nullptr;
2508 SharedVBPtrBase = nullptr;
2509 // Calculate pointer size and alignment. These are used for vfptr and vbprt
2510 // injection.
2511 PointerInfo.Size =
2512 Context.toCharUnitsFromBits(Context.getTargetInfo().getPointerWidth(0));
2513 PointerInfo.Alignment =
2514 Context.toCharUnitsFromBits(Context.getTargetInfo().getPointerAlign(0));
2515 // Respect pragma pack.
2516 if (!MaxFieldAlignment.isZero())
2517 PointerInfo.Alignment = std::min(PointerInfo.Alignment, MaxFieldAlignment);
2518}
2519
2520void
2521MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::layoutNonVirtualBases(const CXXRecordDecl *RD) {
2522 // The MS-ABI lays out all bases that contain leading vfptrs before it lays
2523 // out any bases that do not contain vfptrs. We implement this as two passes
2524 // over the bases. This approach guarantees that the primary base is laid out
2525 // first. We use these passes to calculate some additional aggregated
2526 // information about the bases, such as required alignment and the presence of
2527 // zero sized members.
2528 const ASTRecordLayout *PreviousBaseLayout = nullptr;
2529 // Iterate through the bases and lay out the non-virtual ones.
2530 for (const CXXBaseSpecifier &Base : RD->bases()) {
2531 const CXXRecordDecl *BaseDecl = Base.getType()->getAsCXXRecordDecl();
2532 const ASTRecordLayout &BaseLayout = Context.getASTRecordLayout(BaseDecl);
2533 // Mark and skip virtual bases.
2534 if (Base.isVirtual()) {
2535 HasVBPtr = true;
2536 continue;
2537 }
2538 // Check for a base to share a VBPtr with.
2539 if (!SharedVBPtrBase && BaseLayout.hasVBPtr()) {
2540 SharedVBPtrBase = BaseDecl;
2541 HasVBPtr = true;
2542 }
2543 // Only lay out bases with extendable VFPtrs on the first pass.
2544 if (!BaseLayout.hasExtendableVFPtr())
2545 continue;
2546 // If we don't have a primary base, this one qualifies.
2547 if (!PrimaryBase) {
2548 PrimaryBase = BaseDecl;
2549 LeadsWithZeroSizedBase = BaseLayout.leadsWithZeroSizedBase();
2550 }
2551 // Lay out the base.
2552 layoutNonVirtualBase(RD, BaseDecl, BaseLayout, PreviousBaseLayout);
2553 }
2554 // Figure out if we need a fresh VFPtr for this class.
2555 if (!PrimaryBase && RD->isDynamicClass())
2556 for (CXXRecordDecl::method_iterator i = RD->method_begin(),
2557 e = RD->method_end();
2558 !HasOwnVFPtr && i != e; ++i)
2559 HasOwnVFPtr = i->isVirtual() && i->size_overridden_methods() == 0;
2560 // If we don't have a primary base then we have a leading object that could
2561 // itself lead with a zero-sized object, something we track.
2562 bool CheckLeadingLayout = !PrimaryBase;
2563 // Iterate through the bases and lay out the non-virtual ones.
2564 for (const CXXBaseSpecifier &Base : RD->bases()) {
2565 if (Base.isVirtual())
2566 continue;
2567 const CXXRecordDecl *BaseDecl = Base.getType()->getAsCXXRecordDecl();
2568 const ASTRecordLayout &BaseLayout = Context.getASTRecordLayout(BaseDecl);
2569 // Only lay out bases without extendable VFPtrs on the second pass.
2570 if (BaseLayout.hasExtendableVFPtr()) {
2571 VBPtrOffset = Bases[BaseDecl] + BaseLayout.getNonVirtualSize();
2572 continue;
2573 }
2574 // If this is the first layout, check to see if it leads with a zero sized
2575 // object. If it does, so do we.
2576 if (CheckLeadingLayout) {
2577 CheckLeadingLayout = false;
2578 LeadsWithZeroSizedBase = BaseLayout.leadsWithZeroSizedBase();
2579 }
2580 // Lay out the base.
2581 layoutNonVirtualBase(RD, BaseDecl, BaseLayout, PreviousBaseLayout);
2582 VBPtrOffset = Bases[BaseDecl] + BaseLayout.getNonVirtualSize();
2583 }
2584 // Set our VBPtroffset if we know it at this point.
2585 if (!HasVBPtr)
2586 VBPtrOffset = CharUnits::fromQuantity(-1);
2587 else if (SharedVBPtrBase) {
2588 const ASTRecordLayout &Layout = Context.getASTRecordLayout(SharedVBPtrBase);
2589 VBPtrOffset = Bases[SharedVBPtrBase] + Layout.getVBPtrOffset();
2590 }
2591}
2592
2593static bool recordUsesEBO(const RecordDecl *RD) {
2594 if (!isa<CXXRecordDecl>(RD))
2595 return false;
2596 if (RD->hasAttr<EmptyBasesAttr>())
2597 return true;
2598 if (auto *LVA = RD->getAttr<LayoutVersionAttr>())
2599 // TODO: Double check with the next version of MSVC.
2600 if (LVA->getVersion() <= LangOptions::MSVC2015)
2601 return false;
2602 // TODO: Some later version of MSVC will change the default behavior of the
2603 // compiler to enable EBO by default. When this happens, we will need an
2604 // additional isCompatibleWithMSVC check.
2605 return false;
2606}
2607
2608void MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::layoutNonVirtualBase(
2609 const CXXRecordDecl *RD,
2610 const CXXRecordDecl *BaseDecl,
2611 const ASTRecordLayout &BaseLayout,
2612 const ASTRecordLayout *&PreviousBaseLayout) {
2613 // Insert padding between two bases if the left first one is zero sized or
2614 // contains a zero sized subobject and the right is zero sized or one leads
2615 // with a zero sized base.
2616 bool MDCUsesEBO = recordUsesEBO(RD);
2617 if (PreviousBaseLayout && PreviousBaseLayout->endsWithZeroSizedObject() &&
2618 BaseLayout.leadsWithZeroSizedBase() && !MDCUsesEBO)
2619 Size++;
2620 ElementInfo Info = getAdjustedElementInfo(BaseLayout);
2621 CharUnits BaseOffset;
2622
2623 // Respect the external AST source base offset, if present.
2624 bool FoundBase = false;
2625 if (UseExternalLayout) {
2626 FoundBase = External.getExternalNVBaseOffset(BaseDecl, BaseOffset);
2627 if (FoundBase) {
2628 assert(BaseOffset >= Size && "base offset already allocated");
2629 Size = BaseOffset;
2630 }
2631 }
2632
2633 if (!FoundBase) {
2634 if (MDCUsesEBO && BaseDecl->isEmpty()) {
2635 assert(BaseLayout.getNonVirtualSize() == CharUnits::Zero());
2636 BaseOffset = CharUnits::Zero();
2637 } else {
2638 // Otherwise, lay the base out at the end of the MDC.
2639 BaseOffset = Size = Size.alignTo(Info.Alignment);
2640 }
2641 }
2642 Bases.insert(std::make_pair(BaseDecl, BaseOffset));
2643 Size += BaseLayout.getNonVirtualSize();
2644 PreviousBaseLayout = &BaseLayout;
2645}
2646
2647void MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::layoutFields(const RecordDecl *RD) {
2648 LastFieldIsNonZeroWidthBitfield = false;
2649 for (const FieldDecl *Field : RD->fields())
2650 layoutField(Field);
2651}
2652
2653void MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::layoutField(const FieldDecl *FD) {
2654 if (FD->isBitField()) {
2655 layoutBitField(FD);
2656 return;
2657 }
2658 LastFieldIsNonZeroWidthBitfield = false;
2659 ElementInfo Info = getAdjustedElementInfo(FD);
2660 Alignment = std::max(Alignment, Info.Alignment);
2661 CharUnits FieldOffset;
2662 if (UseExternalLayout)
2663 FieldOffset =
2664 Context.toCharUnitsFromBits(External.getExternalFieldOffset(FD));
2665 else if (IsUnion)
2666 FieldOffset = CharUnits::Zero();
2667 else
2668 FieldOffset = Size.alignTo(Info.Alignment);
2669 placeFieldAtOffset(FieldOffset);
2670 Size = std::max(Size, FieldOffset + Info.Size);
2671}
2672
2673void MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::layoutBitField(const FieldDecl *FD) {
2674 unsigned Width = FD->getBitWidthValue(Context);
2675 if (Width == 0) {
2676 layoutZeroWidthBitField(FD);
2677 return;
2678 }
2679 ElementInfo Info = getAdjustedElementInfo(FD);
2680 // Clamp the bitfield to a containable size for the sake of being able
2681 // to lay them out. Sema will throw an error.
2682 if (Width > Context.toBits(Info.Size))
2683 Width = Context.toBits(Info.Size);
2684 // Check to see if this bitfield fits into an existing allocation. Note:
2685 // MSVC refuses to pack bitfields of formal types with different sizes
2686 // into the same allocation.
2687 if (!UseExternalLayout && !IsUnion && LastFieldIsNonZeroWidthBitfield &&
2688 CurrentBitfieldSize == Info.Size && Width <= RemainingBitsInField) {
2689 placeFieldAtBitOffset(Context.toBits(Size) - RemainingBitsInField);
2690 RemainingBitsInField -= Width;
2691 return;
2692 }
2693 LastFieldIsNonZeroWidthBitfield = true;
2694 CurrentBitfieldSize = Info.Size;
2695 if (UseExternalLayout) {
2696 auto FieldBitOffset = External.getExternalFieldOffset(FD);
2697 placeFieldAtBitOffset(FieldBitOffset);
2698 auto NewSize = Context.toCharUnitsFromBits(
2699 llvm::alignDown(FieldBitOffset, Context.toBits(Info.Alignment)) +
2700 Context.toBits(Info.Size));
2701 Size = std::max(Size, NewSize);
2702 Alignment = std::max(Alignment, Info.Alignment);
2703 } else if (IsUnion) {
2704 placeFieldAtOffset(CharUnits::Zero());
2705 Size = std::max(Size, Info.Size);
2706 // TODO: Add a Sema warning that MS ignores bitfield alignment in unions.
2707 } else {
2708 // Allocate a new block of memory and place the bitfield in it.
2709 CharUnits FieldOffset = Size.alignTo(Info.Alignment);
2710 placeFieldAtOffset(FieldOffset);
2711 Size = FieldOffset + Info.Size;
2712 Alignment = std::max(Alignment, Info.Alignment);
2713 RemainingBitsInField = Context.toBits(Info.Size) - Width;
2714 }
2715}
2716
2717void
2718MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::layoutZeroWidthBitField(const FieldDecl *FD) {
2719 // Zero-width bitfields are ignored unless they follow a non-zero-width
2720 // bitfield.
2721 if (!LastFieldIsNonZeroWidthBitfield) {
2722 placeFieldAtOffset(IsUnion ? CharUnits::Zero() : Size);
2723 // TODO: Add a Sema warning that MS ignores alignment for zero
2724 // sized bitfields that occur after zero-size bitfields or non-bitfields.
2725 return;
2726 }
2727 LastFieldIsNonZeroWidthBitfield = false;
2728 ElementInfo Info = getAdjustedElementInfo(FD);
2729 if (IsUnion) {
2730 placeFieldAtOffset(CharUnits::Zero());
2731 Size = std::max(Size, Info.Size);
2732 // TODO: Add a Sema warning that MS ignores bitfield alignment in unions.
2733 } else {
2734 // Round up the current record size to the field's alignment boundary.
2735 CharUnits FieldOffset = Size.alignTo(Info.Alignment);
2736 placeFieldAtOffset(FieldOffset);
2737 Size = FieldOffset;
2738 Alignment = std::max(Alignment, Info.Alignment);
2739 }
2740}
2741
2742void MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::injectVBPtr(const CXXRecordDecl *RD) {
2743 if (!HasVBPtr || SharedVBPtrBase)
2744 return;
2745 // Inject the VBPointer at the injection site.
2746 CharUnits InjectionSite = VBPtrOffset;
2747 // But before we do, make sure it's properly aligned.
2748 VBPtrOffset = VBPtrOffset.alignTo(PointerInfo.Alignment);
2749 // Determine where the first field should be laid out after the vbptr.
2750 CharUnits FieldStart = VBPtrOffset + PointerInfo.Size;
2751 // Shift everything after the vbptr down, unless we're using an external
2752 // layout.
2753 if (UseExternalLayout) {
2754 // It is possible that there were no fields or bases located after vbptr,
2755 // so the size was not adjusted before.
2756 if (Size < FieldStart)
2757 Size = FieldStart;
2758 return;
2759 }
2760 // Make sure that the amount we push the fields back by is a multiple of the
2761 // alignment.
2762 CharUnits Offset = (FieldStart - InjectionSite)
2763 .alignTo(std::max(RequiredAlignment, Alignment));
2764 Size += Offset;
2765 for (uint64_t &FieldOffset : FieldOffsets)
2766 FieldOffset += Context.toBits(Offset);
2767 for (BaseOffsetsMapTy::value_type &Base : Bases)
2768 if (Base.second >= InjectionSite)
2769 Base.second += Offset;
2770}
2771
2772void MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::injectVFPtr(const CXXRecordDecl *RD) {
2773 if (!HasOwnVFPtr)
2774 return;
2775 // Make sure that the amount we push the struct back by is a multiple of the
2776 // alignment.
2777 CharUnits Offset =
2778 PointerInfo.Size.alignTo(std::max(RequiredAlignment, Alignment));
2779 // Push back the vbptr, but increase the size of the object and push back
2780 // regular fields by the offset only if not using external record layout.
2781 if (HasVBPtr)
2782 VBPtrOffset += Offset;
2783
2784 if (UseExternalLayout) {
2785 // The class may have no bases or fields, but still have a vfptr
2786 // (e.g. it's an interface class). The size was not correctly set before
2787 // in this case.
2788 if (FieldOffsets.empty() && Bases.empty())
2789 Size += Offset;
2790 return;
2791 }
2792
2793 Size += Offset;
2794
2795 // If we're using an external layout, the fields offsets have already
2796 // accounted for this adjustment.
2797 for (uint64_t &FieldOffset : FieldOffsets)
2798 FieldOffset += Context.toBits(Offset);
2799 for (BaseOffsetsMapTy::value_type &Base : Bases)
2800 Base.second += Offset;
2801}
2802
2803void MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::layoutVirtualBases(const CXXRecordDecl *RD) {
2804 if (!HasVBPtr)
2805 return;
2806 // Vtordisps are always 4 bytes (even in 64-bit mode)
2807 CharUnits VtorDispSize = CharUnits::fromQuantity(4);
2808 CharUnits VtorDispAlignment = VtorDispSize;
2809 // vtordisps respect pragma pack.
2810 if (!MaxFieldAlignment.isZero())
2811 VtorDispAlignment = std::min(VtorDispAlignment, MaxFieldAlignment);
2812 // The alignment of the vtordisp is at least the required alignment of the
2813 // entire record. This requirement may be present to support vtordisp
2814 // injection.
2815 for (const CXXBaseSpecifier &VBase : RD->vbases()) {
2816 const CXXRecordDecl *BaseDecl = VBase.getType()->getAsCXXRecordDecl();
2817 const ASTRecordLayout &BaseLayout = Context.getASTRecordLayout(BaseDecl);
2818 RequiredAlignment =
2819 std::max(RequiredAlignment, BaseLayout.getRequiredAlignment());
2820 }
2821 VtorDispAlignment = std::max(VtorDispAlignment, RequiredAlignment);
2822 // Compute the vtordisp set.
2823 llvm::SmallPtrSet<const CXXRecordDecl *, 2> HasVtorDispSet;
2824 computeVtorDispSet(HasVtorDispSet, RD);
2825 // Iterate through the virtual bases and lay them out.
2826 const ASTRecordLayout *PreviousBaseLayout = nullptr;
2827 for (const CXXBaseSpecifier &VBase : RD->vbases()) {
2828 const CXXRecordDecl *BaseDecl = VBase.getType()->getAsCXXRecordDecl();
2829 const ASTRecordLayout &BaseLayout = Context.getASTRecordLayout(BaseDecl);
2830 bool HasVtordisp = HasVtorDispSet.count(BaseDecl) > 0;
2831 // Insert padding between two bases if the left first one is zero sized or
2832 // contains a zero sized subobject and the right is zero sized or one leads
2833 // with a zero sized base. The padding between virtual bases is 4
2834 // bytes (in both 32 and 64 bits modes) and always involves rounding up to
2835 // the required alignment, we don't know why.
2836 if ((PreviousBaseLayout && PreviousBaseLayout->endsWithZeroSizedObject() &&
2837 BaseLayout.leadsWithZeroSizedBase() && !recordUsesEBO(RD)) ||
2838 HasVtordisp) {
2839 Size = Size.alignTo(VtorDispAlignment) + VtorDispSize;
2840 Alignment = std::max(VtorDispAlignment, Alignment);
2841 }
2842 // Insert the virtual base.
2843 ElementInfo Info = getAdjustedElementInfo(BaseLayout);
2844 CharUnits BaseOffset;
2845
2846 // Respect the external AST source base offset, if present.
2847 if (UseExternalLayout) {
2848 if (!External.getExternalVBaseOffset(BaseDecl, BaseOffset))
2849 BaseOffset = Size;
2850 } else
2851 BaseOffset = Size.alignTo(Info.Alignment);
2852
2853 assert(BaseOffset >= Size && "base offset already allocated");
2854
2855 VBases.insert(std::make_pair(BaseDecl,
2856 ASTRecordLayout::VBaseInfo(BaseOffset, HasVtordisp)));
2857 Size = BaseOffset + BaseLayout.getNonVirtualSize();
2858 PreviousBaseLayout = &BaseLayout;
2859 }
2860}
2861
2862void MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::finalizeLayout(const RecordDecl *RD) {
2863 // Respect required alignment. Note that in 32-bit mode Required alignment
2864 // may be 0 and cause size not to be updated.
2865 DataSize = Size;
2866 if (!RequiredAlignment.isZero()) {
2867 Alignment = std::max(Alignment, RequiredAlignment);
2868 auto RoundingAlignment = Alignment;
2869 if (!MaxFieldAlignment.isZero())
2870 RoundingAlignment = std::min(RoundingAlignment, MaxFieldAlignment);
2871 RoundingAlignment = std::max(RoundingAlignment, RequiredAlignment);
2872 Size = Size.alignTo(RoundingAlignment);
2873 }
2874 if (Size.isZero()) {
2875 if (!recordUsesEBO(RD) || !cast<CXXRecordDecl>(RD)->isEmpty()) {
2876 EndsWithZeroSizedObject = true;
2877 LeadsWithZeroSizedBase = true;
2878 }
2879 // Zero-sized structures have size equal to their alignment if a
2880 // __declspec(align) came into play.
2881 if (RequiredAlignment >= MinEmptyStructSize)
2882 Size = Alignment;
2883 else
2884 Size = MinEmptyStructSize;
2885 }
2886
2887 if (UseExternalLayout) {
2888 Size = Context.toCharUnitsFromBits(External.Size);
2889 if (External.Align)
2890 Alignment = Context.toCharUnitsFromBits(External.Align);
2891 }
2892}
2893
2894// Recursively walks the non-virtual bases of a class and determines if any of
2895// them are in the bases with overridden methods set.
2896static bool
2897RequiresVtordisp(const llvm::SmallPtrSetImpl<const CXXRecordDecl *> &
2898 BasesWithOverriddenMethods,
2899 const CXXRecordDecl *RD) {
2900 if (BasesWithOverriddenMethods.count(RD))
2901 return true;
2902 // If any of a virtual bases non-virtual bases (recursively) requires a
2903 // vtordisp than so does this virtual base.
2904 for (const CXXBaseSpecifier &Base : RD->bases())
2905 if (!Base.isVirtual() &&
2906 RequiresVtordisp(BasesWithOverriddenMethods,
2907 Base.getType()->getAsCXXRecordDecl()))
2908 return true;
2909 return false;
2910}
2911
2912void MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder::computeVtorDispSet(
2913 llvm::SmallPtrSetImpl<const CXXRecordDecl *> &HasVtordispSet,
2914 const CXXRecordDecl *RD) const {
2915 // /vd2 or #pragma vtordisp(2): Always use vtordisps for virtual bases with
2916 // vftables.
2917 if (RD->getMSVtorDispMode() == MSVtorDispAttr::ForVFTable) {
2918 for (const CXXBaseSpecifier &Base : RD->vbases()) {
2919 const CXXRecordDecl *BaseDecl = Base.getType()->getAsCXXRecordDecl();
2920 const ASTRecordLayout &Layout = Context.getASTRecordLayout(BaseDecl);
2921 if (Layout.hasExtendableVFPtr())
2922 HasVtordispSet.insert(BaseDecl);
2923 }
2924 return;
2925 }
2926
2927 // If any of our bases need a vtordisp for this type, so do we. Check our
2928 // direct bases for vtordisp requirements.
2929 for (const CXXBaseSpecifier &Base : RD->bases()) {
2930 const CXXRecordDecl *BaseDecl = Base.getType()->getAsCXXRecordDecl();
2931 const ASTRecordLayout &Layout = Context.getASTRecordLayout(BaseDecl);
2932 for (const auto &bi : Layout.getVBaseOffsetsMap())
2933 if (bi.second.hasVtorDisp())
2934 HasVtordispSet.insert(bi.first);
2935 }
2936 // We don't introduce any additional vtordisps if either:
2937 // * A user declared constructor or destructor aren't declared.
2938 // * #pragma vtordisp(0) or the /vd0 flag are in use.
2939 if ((!RD->hasUserDeclaredConstructor() && !RD->hasUserDeclaredDestructor()) ||
2940 RD->getMSVtorDispMode() == MSVtorDispAttr::Never)
2941 return;
2942 // /vd1 or #pragma vtordisp(1): Try to guess based on whether we think it's
2943 // possible for a partially constructed object with virtual base overrides to
2944 // escape a non-trivial constructor.
2945 assert(RD->getMSVtorDispMode() == MSVtorDispAttr::ForVBaseOverride);
2946 // Compute a set of base classes which define methods we override. A virtual
2947 // base in this set will require a vtordisp. A virtual base that transitively
2948 // contains one of these bases as a non-virtual base will also require a
2949 // vtordisp.
2950 llvm::SmallPtrSet<const CXXMethodDecl *, 8> Work;
2951 llvm::SmallPtrSet<const CXXRecordDecl *, 2> BasesWithOverriddenMethods;
2952 // Seed the working set with our non-destructor, non-pure virtual methods.
2953 for (const CXXMethodDecl *MD : RD->methods())
2954 if (MD->isVirtual() && !isa<CXXDestructorDecl>(MD) && !MD->isPure())
2955 Work.insert(MD);
2956 while (!Work.empty()) {
2957 const CXXMethodDecl *MD = *Work.begin();
2958 auto MethodRange = MD->overridden_methods();
2959 // If a virtual method has no-overrides it lives in its parent's vtable.
2960 if (MethodRange.begin() == MethodRange.end())
2961 BasesWithOverriddenMethods.insert(MD->getParent());
2962 else
2963 Work.insert(MethodRange.begin(), MethodRange.end());
2964 // We've finished processing this element, remove it from the working set.
2965 Work.erase(MD);
2966 }
2967 // For each of our virtual bases, check if it is in the set of overridden
2968 // bases or if it transitively contains a non-virtual base that is.
2969 for (const CXXBaseSpecifier &Base : RD->vbases()) {
2970 const CXXRecordDecl *BaseDecl = Base.getType()->getAsCXXRecordDecl();
2971 if (!HasVtordispSet.count(BaseDecl) &&
2972 RequiresVtordisp(BasesWithOverriddenMethods, BaseDecl))
2973 HasVtordispSet.insert(BaseDecl);
2974 }
2975}

2977/// getASTRecordLayout - Get or compute information about the layout of the
2978/// specified record (struct/union/class), which indicates its size and field
2979/// position information.
2980const ASTRecordLayout &
2981ASTContext::getASTRecordLayout(const RecordDecl *D) const {
2982 // These asserts test different things. A record has a definition
2983 // as soon as we begin to parse the definition. That definition is
2984 // not a complete definition (which is what isDefinition() tests)
2985 // until we *finish* parsing the definition.
2986
2987 if (D->hasExternalLexicalStorage() && !D->getDefinition())
2988 getExternalSource()->CompleteType(const_cast<RecordDecl*>(D));
2989
2990 D = D->getDefinition();
2991 assert(D && "Cannot get layout of forward declarations!");
2992 assert(!D->isInvalidDecl() && "Cannot get layout of invalid decl!");
2993 assert(D->isCompleteDefinition() && "Cannot layout type before complete!");
2994
2995 // Look up this layout, if already laid out, return what we have.
2996 // Note that we can't save a reference to the entry because this function
2997 // is recursive.
2998 const ASTRecordLayout *Entry = ASTRecordLayouts[D];
2999 if (Entry) return *Entry;
3000
3001 const ASTRecordLayout *NewEntry = nullptr;
3002
3003 if (isMsLayout(*this)) {
3004 MicrosoftRecordLayoutBuilder Builder(*this);
3005 if (const auto *RD = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(D)) {
3006 Builder.cxxLayout(RD);
3007 NewEntry = new (*this) ASTRecordLayout(
3008 *this, Builder.Size, Builder.Alignment, Builder.Alignment,
3009 Builder.RequiredAlignment,
3010 Builder.HasOwnVFPtr, Builder.HasOwnVFPtr || Builder.PrimaryBase,
3011 Builder.VBPtrOffset, Builder.DataSize, Builder.FieldOffsets,
3012 Builder.NonVirtualSize, Builder.Alignment, CharUnits::Zero(),
3013 Builder.PrimaryBase, false, Builder.SharedVBPtrBase,
3014 Builder.EndsWithZeroSizedObject, Builder.LeadsWithZeroSizedBase,
3015 Builder.Bases, Builder.VBases);
3016 } else {
3017 Builder.layout(D);
3018 NewEntry = new (*this) ASTRecordLayout(
3019 *this, Builder.Size, Builder.Alignment, Builder.Alignment,
3020 Builder.RequiredAlignment,
3021 Builder.Size, Builder.FieldOffsets);
3022 }
3023 } else {
3024 if (const auto *RD = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(D)) {
3025 EmptySubobjectMap EmptySubobjects(*this, RD);
3026 ItaniumRecordLayoutBuilder Builder(*this, &EmptySubobjects);
3027 Builder.Layout(RD);
3028
3029 // In certain situations, we are allowed to lay out objects in the
3030 // tail-padding of base classes. This is ABI-dependent.
3031 // FIXME: this should be stored in the record layout.
3032 bool skipTailPadding =
3033 mustSkipTailPadding(getTargetInfo().getCXXABI(), RD);
3034
3035 // FIXME: This should be done in FinalizeLayout.
3036 CharUnits DataSize =
3037 skipTailPadding ? Builder.getSize() : Builder.getDataSize();
3038 CharUnits NonVirtualSize =
3039 skipTailPadding ? DataSize : Builder.NonVirtualSize;
3040 NewEntry = new (*this) ASTRecordLayout(
3041 *this, Builder.getSize(), Builder.Alignment, Builder.UnadjustedAlignment,
3042 /*RequiredAlignment : used by MS-ABI)*/
3043 Builder.Alignment, Builder.HasOwnVFPtr, RD->isDynamicClass(),
3044 CharUnits::fromQuantity(-1), DataSize, Builder.FieldOffsets,
3045 NonVirtualSize, Builder.NonVirtualAlignment,
3046 EmptySubobjects.SizeOfLargestEmptySubobject, Builder.PrimaryBase,
3047 Builder.PrimaryBaseIsVirtual, nullptr, false, false, Builder.Bases,
3048 Builder.VBases);
3049 } else {
3050 ItaniumRecordLayoutBuilder Builder(*this, /*EmptySubobjects=*/nullptr);
3051 Builder.Layout(D);
3052
3053 NewEntry = new (*this) ASTRecordLayout(
3054 *this, Builder.getSize(), Builder.Alignment, Builder.UnadjustedAlignment,
3055 /*RequiredAlignment : used by MS-ABI)*/
3056 Builder.Alignment, Builder.getSize(), Builder.FieldOffsets);
3057 }
3058 }
3059
3060 ASTRecordLayouts[D] = NewEntry;
3061
3062 if (getLangOpts().DumpRecordLayouts) {
3063 llvm::outs() << "\n*** Dumping AST Record Layout\n";
3064 DumpRecordLayout(D, llvm::outs(), getLangOpts().DumpRecordLayoutsSimple);
3065 }
3066
3067 return *NewEntry;
3068}
3069
3070const CXXMethodDecl *ASTContext::getCurrentKeyFunction(const CXXRecordDecl *RD) {
3071 if (!getTargetInfo().getCXXABI().hasKeyFunctions())
3072 return nullptr;
3073
3074 assert(RD->getDefinition() && "Cannot get key function for forward decl!");
3075 RD = RD->getDefinition();
3076
3077 // Beware:
3078 // 1) computing the key function might trigger deserialization, which might
3079 // invalidate iterators into KeyFunctions
3080 // 2) 'get' on the LazyDeclPtr might also trigger deserialization and
3081 // invalidate the LazyDeclPtr within the map itself
3082 LazyDeclPtr Entry = KeyFunctions[RD];
3083 const Decl *Result =
3084 Entry ? Entry.get(getExternalSource()) : computeKeyFunction(*this, RD);
3085
3086 // Store it back if it changed.
3087 if (Entry.isOffset() || Entry.isValid() != bool(Result))
3088 KeyFunctions[RD] = const_cast<Decl*>(Result);
3089
3090 return cast_or_null<CXXMethodDecl>(Result);
3091}
3092
3093void ASTContext::setNonKeyFunction(const CXXMethodDecl *Method) {
3094 assert(Method == Method->getFirstDecl() &&
3095 "not working with method declaration from class definition");
3096
3097 // Look up the cache entry. Since we're working with the first
3098 // declaration, its parent must be the class definition, which is
3099 // the correct key for the KeyFunctions hash.
3100 const auto &Map = KeyFunctions;
3101 auto I = Map.find(Method->getParent());
3102
3103 // If it's not cached, there's nothing to do.
3104 if (I == Map.end()) return;
3105
3106 // If it is cached, check whether it's the target method, and if so,
3107 // remove it from the cache. Note, the call to 'get' might invalidate
3108 // the iterator and the LazyDeclPtr object within the map.
3109 LazyDeclPtr Ptr = I->second;
3110 if (Ptr.get(getExternalSource()) == Method) {
3111 // FIXME: remember that we did this for module / chained PCH state?
3112 KeyFunctions.erase(Method->getParent());
3113 }
3114}

3121uint64_t ASTContext::getFieldOffset(const ValueDecl *VD) const {
3122 uint64_t OffsetInBits;
3123 if (const FieldDecl *FD = dyn_cast<FieldDecl>(VD)) {
3124 OffsetInBits = ::getFieldOffset(*this, FD);
3125 } else {

3135
3136uint64_t ASTContext::lookupFieldBitOffset(const ObjCInterfaceDecl *OID,
3137 const ObjCImplementationDecl *ID,
3138 const ObjCIvarDecl *Ivar) const {
3139 const ObjCInterfaceDecl *Container = Ivar->getContainingInterface();
3140
3141 // FIXME: We should eliminate the need to have ObjCImplementationDecl passed
3142 // in here; it should never be necessary because that should be the lexical
3143 // decl context for the ivar.
3144
3145 // If we know have an implementation (and the ivar is in it) then
3146 // look up in the implementation layout.
3147 const ASTRecordLayout *RL;
3148 if (ID && declaresSameEntity(ID->getClassInterface(), Container))
3149 RL = &getASTObjCImplementationLayout(ID);
3150 else
3151 RL = &getASTObjCInterfaceLayout(Container);
3152
3153 // Compute field index.
3154 //
3155 // FIXME: The index here is closely tied to how ASTContext::getObjCLayout is
3156 // implemented. This should be fixed to get the information from the layout
3157 // directly.
3158 unsigned Index = 0;
3159
3160 for (const ObjCIvarDecl *IVD = Container->all_declared_ivar_begin();
3161 IVD; IVD = IVD->getNextIvar()) {
3162 if (Ivar == IVD)
3163 break;
3164 ++Index;
3165 }
3166 assert(Index < RL->getFieldCount() && "Ivar is not inside record layout!");
3167
3168 return RL->getFieldOffset(Index);
3169}
3170
3171/// getObjCLayout - Get or compute information about the layout of the
3172/// given interface.
3173///
3174/// \param Impl - If given, also include the layout of the interface's
3175/// implementation. This may differ by including synthesized ivars.
3176const ASTRecordLayout &
3177ASTContext::getObjCLayout(const ObjCInterfaceDecl *D,
3178 const ObjCImplementationDecl *Impl) const {
3179 // Retrieve the definition
3180 if (D->hasExternalLexicalStorage() && !D->getDefinition())
3181 getExternalSource()->CompleteType(const_cast<ObjCInterfaceDecl*>(D));
3182 D = D->getDefinition();
3183 assert(D && D->isThisDeclarationADefinition() && "Invalid interface decl!");
3184
3185 // Look up this layout, if already laid out, return what we have.
3186 const ObjCContainerDecl *Key =
3187 Impl ? (const ObjCContainerDecl*) Impl : (const ObjCContainerDecl*) D;
3188 if (const ASTRecordLayout *Entry = ObjCLayouts[Key])
3189 return *Entry;
3190
3191 // Add in synthesized ivar count if laying out an implementation.
3192 if (Impl) {
3193 unsigned SynthCount = CountNonClassIvars(D);
3194 // If there aren't any synthesized ivars then reuse the interface
3195 // entry. Note we can't cache this because we simply free all
3196 // entries later; however we shouldn't look up implementations
3197 // frequently.
3198 if (SynthCount == 0)
3199 return getObjCLayout(D, nullptr);
3200 }
3201
3202 ItaniumRecordLayoutBuilder Builder(*this, /*EmptySubobjects=*/nullptr);
3203 Builder.Layout(D);
3204
3205 const ASTRecordLayout *NewEntry =
3206 new (*this) ASTRecordLayout(*this, Builder.getSize(),
3207 Builder.Alignment,
3208 Builder.UnadjustedAlignment,
3209 /*RequiredAlignment : used by MS-ABI)*/
3210 Builder.Alignment,
3211 Builder.getDataSize(),
3212 Builder.FieldOffsets);
3213
3214 ObjCLayouts[Key] = NewEntry;
3215
3216 return *NewEntry;
3217}

3219static void PrintOffset(raw_ostream &OS,
3220 CharUnits Offset, unsigned IndentLevel) {
3221 OS << llvm::format("%10" PRId64 " | ", (int64_t)Offset.getQuantity());
3222 OS.indent(IndentLevel * 2);
3223}

3225static void PrintBitFieldOffset(raw_ostream &OS, CharUnits Offset,
3226 unsigned Begin, unsigned Width,
3227 unsigned IndentLevel) {
3228 llvm::SmallString<10> Buffer;
3229 {
3230 llvm::raw_svector_ostream BufferOS(Buffer);
3231 BufferOS << Offset.getQuantity() << ':';
3232 if (Width == 0) {
3233 BufferOS << '-';
3234 } else {
3235 BufferOS << Begin << '-' << (Begin + Width - 1);
3236 }
3237 }
3238
3239 OS << llvm::right_justify(Buffer, 10) << " | ";
3240 OS.indent(IndentLevel * 2);
3241}

3243static void PrintIndentNoOffset(raw_ostream &OS, unsigned IndentLevel) {
3244 OS << " | ";
3245 OS.indent(IndentLevel * 2);
3246}

3248static void DumpRecordLayout(raw_ostream &OS, const RecordDecl *RD,
3249 const ASTContext &C,
3250 CharUnits Offset,
3251 unsigned IndentLevel,
3252 const char* Description,
3253 bool PrintSizeInfo,
3254 bool IncludeVirtualBases) {
3255 const ASTRecordLayout &Layout = C.getASTRecordLayout(RD);
3256 auto CXXRD = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(RD);
3257
3258 PrintOffset(OS, Offset, IndentLevel);
3259 OS << C.getTypeDeclType(const_cast<RecordDecl*>(RD)).getAsString();
3260 if (Description)
3261 OS << ' ' << Description;
3262 if (CXXRD && CXXRD->isEmpty())
3263 OS << " (empty)";
3264 OS << '\n';
3265
3266 IndentLevel++;
3267
3268 // Dump bases.
3269 if (CXXRD) {
3270 const CXXRecordDecl *PrimaryBase = Layout.getPrimaryBase();
3271 bool HasOwnVFPtr = Layout.hasOwnVFPtr();
3272 bool HasOwnVBPtr = Layout.hasOwnVBPtr();
3273
3274 // Vtable pointer.
3275 if (CXXRD->isDynamicClass() && !PrimaryBase && !isMsLayout(C)) {
3276 PrintOffset(OS, Offset, IndentLevel);
3277 OS << '(' << *RD << " vtable pointer)\n";
3278 } else if (HasOwnVFPtr) {
3279 PrintOffset(OS, Offset, IndentLevel);
3280 // vfptr (for Microsoft C++ ABI)
3281 OS << '(' << *RD << " vftable pointer)\n";
3282 }
3283
3284 // Collect nvbases.
3285 SmallVector<const CXXRecordDecl *, 4> Bases;
3286 for (const CXXBaseSpecifier &Base : CXXRD->bases()) {
3287 assert(!Base.getType()->isDependentType() &&
3288 "Cannot layout class with dependent bases.");
3289 if (!Base.isVirtual())
3290 Bases.push_back(Base.getType()->getAsCXXRecordDecl());
3291 }
3292
3293 // Sort nvbases by offset.
3294 llvm::stable_sort(
3295 Bases, [&](const CXXRecordDecl *L, const CXXRecordDecl *R) {
3296 return Layout.getBaseClassOffset(L) < Layout.getBaseClassOffset(R);
3297 });
3298
3299 // Dump (non-virtual) bases
3300 for (const CXXRecordDecl *Base : Bases) {
3301 CharUnits BaseOffset = Offset + Layout.getBaseClassOffset(Base);
3302 DumpRecordLayout(OS, Base, C, BaseOffset, IndentLevel,
3303 Base == PrimaryBase ? "(primary base)" : "(base)",
3304 /*PrintSizeInfo=*/false,
3305 /*IncludeVirtualBases=*/false);
3306 }
3307
3308 // vbptr (for Microsoft C++ ABI)
3309 if (HasOwnVBPtr) {
3310 PrintOffset(OS, Offset + Layout.getVBPtrOffset(), IndentLevel);
3311 OS << '(' << *RD << " vbtable pointer)\n";
3312 }
3313 }
3314
3315 // Dump fields.
3316 uint64_t FieldNo = 0;
3317 for (RecordDecl::field_iterator I = RD->field_begin(),
3318 E = RD->field_end(); I != E; ++I, ++FieldNo) {
3319 const FieldDecl &Field = **I;
3320 uint64_t LocalFieldOffsetInBits = Layout.getFieldOffset(FieldNo);
3321 CharUnits FieldOffset =
3322 Offset + C.toCharUnitsFromBits(LocalFieldOffsetInBits);
3323
3324 // Recursively dump fields of record type.
3325 if (auto RT = Field.getType()->getAs<RecordType>()) {
3326 DumpRecordLayout(OS, RT->getDecl(), C, FieldOffset, IndentLevel,
3327 Field.getName().data(),
3328 /*PrintSizeInfo=*/false,
3329 /*IncludeVirtualBases=*/true);
3330 continue;
3331 }
3332
3333 if (Field.isBitField()) {
3334 uint64_t LocalFieldByteOffsetInBits = C.toBits(FieldOffset - Offset);
3335 unsigned Begin = LocalFieldOffsetInBits - LocalFieldByteOffsetInBits;
3336 unsigned Width = Field.getBitWidthValue(C);
3337 PrintBitFieldOffset(OS, FieldOffset, Begin, Width, IndentLevel);
3338 } else {
3339 PrintOffset(OS, FieldOffset, IndentLevel);
3340 }
3341 OS << Field.getType().getAsString() << ' ' << Field << '\n';
3342 }
3343
3344 // Dump virtual bases.
3345 if (CXXRD && IncludeVirtualBases) {
3346 const ASTRecordLayout::VBaseOffsetsMapTy &VtorDisps =
3347 Layout.getVBaseOffsetsMap();
3348
3349 for (const CXXBaseSpecifier &Base : CXXRD->vbases()) {
3350 assert(Base.isVirtual() && "Found non-virtual class!");
3351 const CXXRecordDecl *VBase = Base.getType()->getAsCXXRecordDecl();
3352
3353 CharUnits VBaseOffset = Offset + Layout.getVBaseClassOffset(VBase);
3354
3355 if (VtorDisps.find(VBase)->second.hasVtorDisp()) {
3356 PrintOffset(OS, VBaseOffset - CharUnits::fromQuantity(4), IndentLevel);
3357 OS << "(vtordisp for vbase " << *VBase << ")\n";
3358 }
3359
3360 DumpRecordLayout(OS, VBase, C, VBaseOffset, IndentLevel,
3361 VBase == Layout.getPrimaryBase() ?
3362 "(primary virtual base)" : "(virtual base)",
3363 /*PrintSizeInfo=*/false,
3364 /*IncludeVirtualBases=*/false);
3365 }
3366 }
3367
3368 if (!PrintSizeInfo) return;
3369
3370 PrintIndentNoOffset(OS, IndentLevel - 1);
3371 OS << "[sizeof=" << Layout.getSize().getQuantity();
3372 if (CXXRD && !isMsLayout(C))
3373 OS << ", dsize=" << Layout.getDataSize().getQuantity();
3374 OS << ", align=" << Layout.getAlignment().getQuantity();
3375
3376 if (CXXRD) {
3377 OS << ",\n";
3378 PrintIndentNoOffset(OS, IndentLevel - 1);
3379 OS << " nvsize=" << Layout.getNonVirtualSize().getQuantity();
3380 OS << ", nvalign=" << Layout.getNonVirtualAlignment().getQuantity();
3381 }
3382 OS << "]\n";
3383}

3385void ASTContext::DumpRecordLayout(const RecordDecl *RD,
3386 raw_ostream &OS,
3387 bool Simple) const {
3388 if (!Simple) {
3389 ::DumpRecordLayout(OS, RD, *this, CharUnits(), 0, nullptr,
3390 /*PrintSizeInfo*/true,
3391 /*IncludeVirtualBases=*/true);
3392 return;
3393 }
3394
3395 // The "simple" format is designed to be parsed by the
3396 // layout-override testing code. There shouldn't be any external
3397 // uses of this format --- when LLDB overrides a layout, it sets up
3398 // the data structures directly --- so feel free to adjust this as
3399 // you like as long as you also update the rudimentary parser for it
3400 // in libFrontend.
3401
3402 const ASTRecordLayout &Info = getASTRecordLayout(RD);
3403 OS << "Type: " << getTypeDeclType(RD).getAsString() << "\n";
3404 OS << "\nLayout: ";
3405 OS << "<ASTRecordLayout\n";
3406 OS << " Size:" << toBits(Info.getSize()) << "\n";
3407 if (!isMsLayout(*this))
3408 OS << " DataSize:" << toBits(Info.getDataSize()) << "\n";
3409 OS << " Alignment:" << toBits(Info.getAlignment()) << "\n";
3410 OS << " FieldOffsets: [";
3411 for (unsigned i = 0, e = Info.getFieldCount(); i != e; ++i) {
3412 if (i) OS << ", ";
3413 OS << Info.getFieldOffset(i);
3414 }
3415 OS << "]>\n";
3416}
